.<br /><br />Semtnaitcally killing init is completely wrong. Because it will kill<br />the whole system.<br /><br />And I don't mean that in "now init won't spawn new things". I mean<br />that in "now we don't have a child reaper any more, and the system<br />will be dead because we'll panic on exit".<br /><br />So it's not about the controlling tty, it's about fundamental kernel<br />internal consistency guarantees.<br /><br />See<br /><br />        write_unlock_irq(&amp;tasklist_lock);<br />        if (unlikely(pid_ns == &amp;init_pid_ns)) {<br />                panic("Attempted to kill init! exitcode=0x%08x\n",<br />                        father-&gt;signal-&gt;group_exit_code ?: father-&gt;exit_code);<br />        }<br /><br />in kernel/exit.c.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
